INSERT INTO `tbl_notice_board` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `link`, `status`) VALUES
(6, '3rd January amendments', '<div id="cke_pastebin">\r\n	1.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Income Tax department has started sending reminder by email to those who have not filed their Income tax return for assessment year 2014-2015.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div id="cke_pastebin">\r\n	2.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Cost records applicable if turnover exceeds Rs.35 crores. Cost audit applicability if turnover exceeds Rs.50 Crores (Regulated Industry), Rs.100 Crores (Others). Refer Detailed Notification at: &nbsp;http://www.mca.gov.in/Ministry/pdf/Amendment_Rules_01012014.pdf. [MCA Notification dated 31.12.2014].<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div id="cke_pastebin">\r\n	3.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>ROC Delhi and Haryana reduced office hours for public visiting from 10.30 AM to 12.30 PM.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div id="cke_pastebin">\r\n	4.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Convert to freehold till 31.12.2015. Residential leases already expired in areas such as Karol Bagh, Jhandewalan, Paharganj etc. in Delhi at 2 lakh per 100 sq metre.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div id="cke_pastebin">\r\n	5.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Amendments made in IEC code application (W.e.f. 01/01/2015). Fees revised from Rs. 250 to Rs. 500, application made only in online mode, etc.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div id="cke_pastebin">\r\n	6.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>DVAT Delhi is starting special drive for speedy disposal of objections relating to mismatch of 2A and 2B for the year 2012-2013 shall continue on 8th, 9th and 10th January 2015.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div id="cke_pastebin">\r\n	7.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Online applications invited by CAG from CA firms/LLP for empanelment for appointment as auditors of Government Companies/Corporations 2015-2016. Please visit www.saiindia.gov.in.</div>', '', 1),
(7, 'News 6th January 2015', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>If dividend is not received, disallowance u/s 14A of the Income Tax Act cannot be made. &nbsp;[ACIT vs. M/s. Bharat Hotels Ltd. Honorable ITAT Delhi].</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Most TP audit report by CAs unreliable with pathetic professional work. [Wrigley India Private Ltd vs. ACIT (ITAT Delhi)].</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>DVAT dealers get another chance to approach Ward Objection Hearing Authority on 8th, 9th and10th January to settle objections relating to mismatch of 2A and 2B for 2012-2013.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	4.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Department to frame assessment for Q4 of 2013-2014 and review other quarters. Check status of matching of purchases in Mismatch Report and revise by 16.01.2015. [DVAT Notice].</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Excise duty exemption cannot be denied merely because the certificates were in the name of intermediary through whom the material was supplied for approved projects. [Commissioner of Central Excise, Jaipur vs. Kamdhenu Ispat Ltd. (New Delhi &ndash; CESTAT)]</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	6.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>W.e.f. 01.01.2015, only online application for IEC. IEC certificates also to be issued in digital format in two days. [Policy Circular 15 (RE-2013)/2009-2014 of 31-12-2014].</p>', '', 1),
(8, 'Private Placements under New Companies Act 2013', '<p align="center">\r\n	<strong>PROCEDURAL REQUIREMENTS OF PRIVATE PLACEMENT UNDER THE COMPANIES ACT, 2013</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Introduction</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;The procedural requirements and compliance under the Private placement have undergone drastic changes under the Companies Act, 2013 (the Act) and the Rules relating to the private placement have been notified w.e.f. 1st April, 2014 under the Companies (Prospectus and Allotment of Securities) Rules, 2014. Private placement is one of the important routes for raising funds by the companies- it being the fastest, as it bye-passes certain compliance requirements under the strict Regulatory procedures. Further, under the Companies Act, 1956, the conditions relating to private placement were applicable only to public companies whereas, in the present Act, the private placement of shares and debentures shall be applicable to both, private limited companies as well as to public companies.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Private placement of securities</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Securities mean equity shares, preference shares, debentures, convertible instruments and redeemable instruments. The Act uses the words issue of securities and not shares. Thus, it has wide coverage and includes almost all the instruments and other marketable securities as mentioned above.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Provisions of Private Placement under the Companies Act, 2013</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>3. </strong>Chapter III, Part II of the Act, 2013 deals with the provisions related to the private placement of securities. Further, section 42 of the Act contains the provisions relating to offer or invitation for subscription to securities on private placement.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Private Placement is defined under the <em>Explanation</em> II to section 42, which reads as follows:&mdash;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:22.65pt;">\r\n	&quot;any offer of securities or invitation to subscribe to securities to a select group of persons by a company (other than by way of public offer) through issue of a private placement offer letter and which satisfies the conditions specified in this section&quot;. Further, as per section 42(2)(1), the offer of securities or invitation to subscribe to securities shall be made to such number of persons not exceeding fifty or such higher number as may be prescribed (excluding qualified institutional buyers and employees of the company being offered securities under a scheme of employees stock option(ESOP) as per provisions of clause (b) of sub-section (1) of section 62), in a financial year and on such conditions (including the form and manner of private placement) as may be prescribed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Thus, it can be concluded that issuance of ESOPs, Rights Issues, securities offered through public issues, Depository Receipts issued outside India, foreign securities have different norms to be followed and will not be under the Private Placement norms. These private placement norms shall be applicable if the offer is made to a person who is currently not an equity shareholder of the company.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Deemed to be an offer to the Public</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>4. </strong>As per Section 42(4) of the Act, any offer or invitation not in compliance with the provisions of this Section shall be treated as a public offer and all the provisions of this Act, and the Securities Contracts (Regulation) Act, 1956 (42 of 1956) (SCRA) and the Securities and Exchange Board of India Act, 1992 (15 of 1992) (SEBI) are required to be complied with. This provision has been introduced in order to plug the loophole wherein Sahara had issued hybrid instruments to several lakhs of investors and yet claimed that SEBI did not have jurisdiction. The case related to Sahara is known to everybody. For the sake of brevity the same has not been repeated herein.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Further, the <em>Explanation</em> I to section 42 of the Act clearly states that if a company, whether listed or unlisted, makes an offer to allot or invites subscription or allots or enters into an agreement to allot securities to more than the prescribed number of persons, whether the payment for the securities has been received or not or whether the company intends to list out its securities or not on any recognized stock exchange in or outside India, the same shall be deemed to be an offer to the public and shall, accordingly, be governed by the provisions of Part I of the Chapter, <em>i.e.,</em> will come under the clutches of the SEBI and the SCRA.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Operative portion of the section</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>5. </strong>Private Placement provision stipulates that all monies payable towards subscription of securities by private placement shall be paid through cheque or demand draft or through other banking channels but not by cash. Further, a company making an offer or invitation under this section shall allot its securities within a period of 60 days from the receipt of application money. If the company is not able to allot the securities within the specified period, the application money is to be refunded within a period of 15 days from completion of 60 days. The money raised by the issue of offer or invitation shall be in a separate bank account and cannot be used until allotted. However, the said money can be utilised for adjustment against allotment of securities or for the repayment of monies where the company is unable to allot securities.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Restrictions on issue of private placement</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>6. </strong>(<em>a</em>) No fresh offer or invitation under private placement is possible unless the allotments with respect to any offer made earlier have been completed or that offer or invitation has been withdrawn or abandoned by the company.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	(<em>b</em>) All offers under the private placement route shall be made only to such persons whose names are recorded by the company prior to the invitation to subscribe and that such persons shall receive the offer by name, and that a complete record of such offers shall be kept by the company in such manner as may be prescribed and complete information about such offer shall be filed with the Registrar within a period of 30 days of circulation of relevant private placement offer letter. Again these provisions are included due to the fall out of Sahara&#39;s Case.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	(<em>c</em>) The company offering securities under the private placement is barred from releasing any public advertisements or utilise any media, marketing or distribution channels or agents to inform the public at large about such an offer.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Procedural requirements under the Rules</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7. </strong>A company making an offer or invitation under the private placement route has to comply with the procedural requirements prescribed under rule 14 which are listed below:&mdash;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.1 <em>Information of private placement offer letter</em> - </strong>Without prejudice to the provisions contained under section 26 of the Act, namely, the matters to be stated in the prospectus, a company may make an offer or invitation to subscribe to securities through issue of a private placement offer letter. The same shall be in Form PAS-4. The private placement offer letter shall broadly contain the following:-</p>\r\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>i</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					General Information about the company, including details of default in statutory dues, loans from banks and financial institutions, deposits and interest, etc.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>ii</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Particulars of the offer</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>iii</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Disclosures with regard to interest of directors, litigation, etc.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>iv</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Related party transactions entered into during the last three financial years immediately preceding the year of circulation of offer letter, including with regard to loans made or guarantees given or securities provided.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>v</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Summary of reservations or qualifications or adverse remarks of auditors in the last five financial years immediately preceding the year of circulation of offer letter and their impact on the financial statements and financial position of the company and the corrective steps taken and proposed to be taken by the company.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>vi</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Details of inquiry, inspections or investigations initiated or conducted under the Companies Act or any previous Company law in the last three years immediately preceding the year of circulation of offer letter in the case of company and all its subsidiaries.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>vii</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Details of acts of material frauds committed against the company in the last three years, if any, and if so, the action taken by the company.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>viii</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Financial position of the company.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>ix</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:556px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					A declaration by the Directors that: (<em>a</em>) the company has complied with the provisions of the Act and the Rules made thereunder, (<em>b</em>) compliance with the Act and the Rules does not imply that payment of dividend or interest or repayment of debentures, if any applicable, is guaranteed by the Central Government. (<em>c</em>) the monies received under the offer shall be used only for the purpose and objects indicated in the offer letter.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.2 <em>Time-limit</em> - </strong>The offer for private placement shall be accompanied by an application form serially numbered and addressed specifically to the person concerned to whom the offer is made. The same has to be sent to him either in writing or through electronic mode within 30 days of recording the names of such persons as are provided in section 42(7) of the Act.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.3 <em>Invalid offer </em>- </strong>No person other than the person so addressed in the application form shall be allowed to apply through such application form. Any application not conforming to this condition shall be treated as invalid.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.4 <em>Approval of shareholders</em> - </strong>The offer of securities or invitation to make a private placement has to be previously approved by the shareholders of the company by a special resolution. The special resolution has to be passed for each of the offers or each of the invitations, as the case may be.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.5 <em>Justification of the offer price </em>- </strong>In the explanatory statement annexed to the notice for the general meeting for securing the special resolution of the shareholders, the basis or justification for the price including premium, if any, at which the offer or invitation is being made shall be disclosed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.6 <em>Non-convertible Debentures offer</em> - </strong>In the case of offer or invitation for non-convertible debentures, it is sufficient if the company passes a special resolution only once in a year for all the offers or invitations for such debentures during the said year.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.7 <em>Restrictions on number of persons to whom the offer can be made</em> - </strong>The offer or invitation shall be made to not more than 200 persons in the aggregate in a financial year. But any offer or invitation made to qualified institutional buyers or to employees of the company under a scheme of employees stock option as per provisions of clause (<em>b</em>) of sub-section (1) of section 62 shall not be considered while calculating the limit of 200 persons. The cap of 200 persons would be reckoned individually for each kind of security that is being offered under private placement, <em>i.e.,</em> it will be counted for each instrument, namely, equity share, preference share or debenture, etc.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.8 <em>Restriction on fresh offer or invitation</em> - </strong>As per Section 42(3), no fresh offer or invitation under private placement is possible unless the allotments with respect to any offer made earlier have been completed or that offer or invitation has been withdrawn or abandoned by the company. Thus, this provision shall apply in respect of an offer or invitation of each kind of security and no offer or invitation of another kind of security shall be made, unless allotment with respect to offer or invitation made earlier in respect of any other kind of security is completed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.9 <em>Value of size of the offer</em> - </strong>The value of such offer or invitation per person shall be with an investment size of not less than Rs. 20,000 face value of the securities. No cash is allowed, payment is to be made only through cheque and demand draft.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.10 <em>Company to maintain bank account details</em> - </strong>The company shall keep the record of the bank account from where such payments for subscriptions have been received and, thus, the payment cannot be made by the subscriber other than the bank account of the person subscribing to such securities. However, in case of joint holders, the subscription to the securities can be made from the bank account of the person whose name appears first in the application.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.11 <em>Maintenance of records - </em></strong>The company shall maintain a complete record of private placement offers in Form PAS-5, namely, when the approval of the Board or shareholders was obtained for the private placement offer, amount of offer, date of circulation of private placement offer letter, details of the persons to whom private placement offers have been circulated like, name, father&#39;s name, complete address, phone number, email id and also initial of the officer of the company designated to keep the said record.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.12 <em>Filing of returns with Registrar &amp; SEBI - </em></strong>The company has to file a copy of such record maintained in PAS-5 alongwith the private placement offer letter in PAS-4 with the Registrar with fee as provided in the Companies (Registration Offices and Fees) Rules, 2014. In case the company is a listed entity, the same has to be filed with the SEBI within a period of thirty days of circulation of the private placement offer letter. It has also been clarified that the date of private placement offer letter shall be deemed to be the date of circulation of private placement offer letter.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.13 <em>Return of allotment - </em></strong>The company shall file the return of allotment of securities with the Registrar within 30 days of allotment in Form PAS-3 with the fee as provided in the Companies (Registration Offices and Fees) Rules, 2014 alongwith a complete list of all security holders containing: (<em>i</em>) the full name, address, Permanent Account Number and E-mail Id of such security holder, (<em>ii</em>) class of security held, (<em>iii</em>) the date of allotment of security, (<em>iv</em>) the number of securities held, nominal value and amount paid on such securities and particulars of consideration received, if the securities were issued for consideration other than cash.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>7.14 <em>Provisions applicable to non-banking financial companies &amp; Housing Finance Companies-Interface between Companies Act, 2013 &amp; RBI and NHB Guidelines - </em></strong>The provisions of private placement of securities, as regards restriction on number of persons to whom the offer is to be given, investment size and payment to be made for subscription to securities shall be made from the bank account of the person subscribing to such securities, shall not be applicable to:</p>\r\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>a</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:555px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Non-banking financial companies which are registered with the Reserve Bank of India under the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934; and</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="width:47px;">\r\n				<p align="right">\r\n					(<em>b</em>)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:19px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="width:555px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					Housing Finance Companies which are registered with the National Housing Bank (NHB) under the National Housing Bank Act, 1987:</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>\r\n	if they are complying with the regulations made by the RBI or NHB in respect of offer or invitation to be issued on private placement basis.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	There is also a rider that in case the RBI or the NHB has not specified similar Regulations, then such companies shall comply with the provisions relating to the restriction on the number of persons to whom the offer or invitation shall be made alongswith explanation given under sub-rule 2(<em>b</em>) of rule 14 and the amount of investment size specified under sub-rule 2(<em>c</em>) of rule 14.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Penalty for violation</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>8.</strong>According to section 42(10) of the Act, if a company makes an offer or accepts monies in contravention of section 42 of the Act, the company, its promoters and directors shall be liable for a penalty which may extend to the amount involved in offer or invitation or two crore rupees, whichever is higher. The company is also required to refund all monies to subscribers within a period of thirty days of the order imposing the penalty.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Conclusion</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>10. </strong>The Companies Act, 2013 has made stringent requirements for raising money by way of private placements since instances of entities misusing the private placement route to garner funds have come to light. Now, the Act and the Rules have taken care of the all the nuances and requirements and has come out with strict guidelines, which will pave way for better governance of all companies, including private limited companies. The procedure stipulated is a lengthy one with more burden to keep all the records while placing private placement, but it will go a long way to ensure transparency in the system and will boost the investors&#39; confidence.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><em>Disclaimer: The views expressed in this write up are personal views of author and is not a substitute of professional advise. Any person relying on this write up must do at its own risk and should take expert opinion before making any decision.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>', '', 1);

